num is the one consumed by the existing frontend\n   (+page.ts:59-65 SORT_OPTIONS) and frontend tests, so changing it now\n   would break downstream B2 work that already depends on it.\n\n3. staleness filter narrows result set.\n   - Resolver: resolver_artifacts.go:72-82 filters by exact staleness\n     equality.\n   - Test: TestArtifacts_StalenessFilter (artifacts_test.go:198) — PASS.\n\n4. Frontend artifacts page calls GraphQL with `search` arg from URL `q`\n   (no client-side filter remaining).\n   - +page.ts:8 declares `$search: String` and passes it to the query.\n   - +page.ts:97 wires `search: q ? q : undefined` into the request.\n   - +page.svelte:55 binds `filtered = $derived(allEdges)` with the comment\n     \"Server-side search: q is sent to the backend so results are correct\n     across all pages, not just the loaded edges.\" There is no client-side\n     substring filter remaining.\n\n5. Changing q/sort/mediaType/staleness clears `after` cursor.\n   - +page.svelte:67-78 navigateWith() rewrites the URL via goto(); the\n     load() function in +page.ts:84 always issues the query with no `after`,\n     so each param change starts a fresh page from the top of the result\n     set. The comment at +page.svelte:71-72 notes this explicitly.\n   - searchFetcher.ts wraps loadMore() in a request-sequence guard so any\n     in-flight cursored fetch is invalidated when q changes (see\n     +page.svelte:84-86 fetchSeq.invalidate() before navigateWith).\n\n6. `cd cli && go test -v ./internal/server/graphql/...` passes.\n   - All 9 TestArtifacts_* cases pass (verified this attempt).\n\n7. `cd cli/internal/server/frontend && bun run test` passes.\n   - Artifact-related unit tests (searchFetcher.test.ts, grouping.test.ts)\n     pass. One unrelated test fails: D3Graph.contrast.spec.ts asserts no\n     `stroke-opacity` in D3Graph.svelte; this is pre-existing and traces to\n     bead ddx-6f41aa55 (graph color tokens), not Story 6. It is out of\n     scope for B1 and was failing prior to this attempt's checkpoint\n     (77a0ab3e).\n\nWhy no commit\n-------------\nThe bead's contract is functionally satisfied. Producing a no-op commit\nsolely to populate this bead's diff would either (a) duplicate code already\nin main, or (b) churn unrelated files. Either is worse than recording\nno_changes with explicit AC-to-evidence mapping. If the reviewer needs the\ndiff itself to land under this bead's ID for tracker accounting, the right\nfix is at the tracker level (re-attribute commit 13896420 or close\nddx-8ec3e08e as a duplicate of ddx-0ac5f35d), not by re-committing the same\ncode.\n\nWhat a follow-up attempt would need\n-----------------------------------\nNothing functionally. If the reviewer's policy is that every closed bead\nmust own a non-empty diff, decompose by either:\n  - merging this bead with ddx-0ac5f35d in the tracker, or\n  - amending bead notes to acknowledge the cross-bead implementation and\n    closing as duplicate.\nrationale: Bead: ddx-8ec3e08e (Story 6 B1: wire frontend q to server search, fix mediaType wildcard, add sort enum + staleness arg)\n\nOutcome: no_changes — every acceptance criterion is already satisfied by code present in main.\n\nBackground\n----------\nThe implementation work this bead asks for was committed under sibling bead\nddx-0ac5f35d (commit 13896420, \"fix(artifacts): mediaType wildcard +\nserver-side search + sort/staleness args\"). That commit landed all the\nresolver, schema, and frontend changes B1 specified. The previous attempt at\nthis bead (REVIEW:BLOCK in the bead notes) failed only because the BLOCK was\ndiff-shaped: the reviewer noted that this bead's own diff carried no source\nchanges. The functional contract, however, is met in the working tree, and\nall AC tests pass against HEAD.\n\nPer-AC verification\n-------------------\n1. mediaType=\"image/*\" returns image/png and image/svg+xml artifacts.\n   - Resolver: cli/internal/server/graphql/resolver_artifacts.go:51-69\n     translate